Part I - Ford Gobike Data Exploration¶

by Teniola Alade¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area in the year 2019.

# adding new columns
ford_gobike_clean['start_year'] = ford_gobike_clean.start_time.dt.year
ford_gobike_clean['start_month'] = ford_gobike_clean.start_time.dt.month_name()
ford_gobike_clean['start_day'] = ford_gobike_clean.start_time.dt.day_name()
ford_gobike_clean['start_day_id'] = ford_gobike_clean.start_time.dt.day_of_week
ford_gobike_clean['start_hour'] = ford_gobike_clean.start_time.dt.hour


ford_gobike_clean['end_month'] = ford_gobike_clean.end_time.dt.month_name()
ford_gobike_clean['end_day'] = ford_gobike_clean.end_time.dt.day_name() 
ford_gobike_clean['end_day_id'] = ford_gobike_clean.end_time.dt.day_of_week

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset consists of information about 174,952 bike rides with 18 columns. There are 8 numerical, 2 datetime, 7 strings and 1 boolean type data.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the duration of the ford_gobike rides in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the duration of the trip is mostly affected by the age of the user, the day of the week, gender and by the user type; subscriber or member

In [29]:
# logarthmic scale transformation on a histogram
# there's a long tail in the distribution, so i'll be using a log scale to deep dive
log_binsize = 0.1
log_bins = 10 ** np.arange(0.0, np.log10(ford_gobike_clean['duration_sec'].max()) + log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[12, 6])
plt.hist(data = ford_gobike_clean, x = 'duration_sec', bins = log_bins)
x_y_t('Duration (sec)','Count','Distribution of Trip Duration')
plt.xscale('log')
tick_locs = [40,50,60,90,120,180,300,500,800,1200,2000,3600,6000,10000,15000,25000]
plt.xticks(tick_locs, tick_locs)
plt.xlim([40,25000])
plt.show()

The logarithm scale shows that this distibution is unimodal, peaking around the 500 to 700 seconds range. While a signinicant number of the bike rides lasted round the 300 to 900 sec range, there was not a lot around the 180 sec mark and over the 2000 sec mark.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

- The trip duration is inversely proportional to the age. The older the user, the sorter the trip and vice versa.
- The female and other gender had marginally longer trip duration than the male gender.
- The customers rode the bike for a longer duration than the subscribers.
- The weekend bike ride had longer duration than the weekdays.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

- It was surprising that although the total count of male gender was significantly higher than the other genders, it had the shortest trip duration.
- It's also interesting that the customers had longer trips than the subscribers.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

- The multivariate exploration showed that there is a weak negative correlation between the duration and the age of the user regardless of the age and the user-type. However, it's more apparent that the gender of the user has more effect.

- It also showed that the other gender category had a suprisingly more part to play than the rest of the gender on the daily time spent on the bike  recording the highest regardless of the day of the week and it impacts the customer user-type duration because it takes majority of the proportion.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

- I extended my investigaton of the duration and days of week, It was interesting to find that the customer category recorded the highest time on the bike but not surprising since the customers are majorly the other gender and the subscribers are mainly the male gender.
- I extended my investigation of the duration against age, it was interesting to find that the same trend is apparent when both the gender and user-type variables were introduced
- Looking back at age against user-type, it is not surprising to find that there is not any interaction effect between the age of the user-type and duration of the bike trip.

Conclusions¶

To sum up, there was a weak negative correlarion between the time spent on the bike ride and the age of the user; the older the user, the shorter the time and vice versa. In addition, the other gender category had more part to play on the daily time spent on the trip than any other gender, recording the highest duration regardless of the day of the week, and this significantly impacted the customer-user type duration as it takes majority of the proportion
